Part (c)

# Insert code or written answer here
eigen(southAmericaCorrelationMatrix)$values
## [1] 2.59136094 1.30474169 0.06277743 0.04111993

Part (d)

# Insert code or written answer here
eigen(southAmericaCorrelationMatrix)$values>1
## [1]  TRUE  TRUE FALSE FALSE
eigen(southAmericaCorrelationMatrix)$values>0.7
## [1]  TRUE  TRUE FALSE FALSE
# Written answer directly below

The Kaisers and Jolliffes criteria do not support the World Bank Groups assertion that access to Water, Electricity, Sanitation, and Education are all aspects or dimensions of a single multidimensional measure of poverty. This is because not all of the eigen values are above the 1.0 and 0.7 levels used as Kaiser and Jolliffe criteria respectively. The third and fourth eigen values are below both thresholds.

Exercise 2.02 - New Enterprises in South Africa

Part (a)

# Insert code or written answer here
obstacleEigenValues = c(20.225, 8.432, 2.356, 2.156, 1.835, 0.895, 0.779, 0.701, 0.653, 0.601, 0.552,0.492,0.452,0.401,0.369,0.301,0.215,0.198,0.182,0.173, 0.167, 0.161, 0.157, 0.152, 0.107, 0.101, 0.040, 0.037, 0.034)

Part (b)

# Insert code or written answer here
plot(obstacleEigenValues, type = "b")

Part (c)

# Written answer directly below

The intrinsic dimensionality found by using the inflection point criterion or scree test would be 2, as the the inflection point occurs at the third eigenvalue.

Part (d)

# Insert code or written answer here
length(which(obstacleEigenValues>1))
## [1] 5
#obstacleEigenValues>1

Part (e)

# Insert code or written answer here
length(which(obstacleEigenValues>0.7))
## [1] 8
#obstacleEigenValues>0.7

Part (f)

# Written answer directly below

The intrinsic dimensionality found by using the inflection point criterion [Part c], Kaisers criterion [Part d], and Jolliffes criterion [Part e] are all different. The intrinsic dimensionality of Part c is the smallest, since the graph generated in Part B seems to show the eigen values leveling off once the third eigen value is reached. The intrinsic dimensionality of Part e is the largest, since the threshold of 0.7 used as Jolliffes criterion is less than the threshold used as Kaisers criterion, and the shape and y axis scale of the scree plot from Part b is influenced significantly by the 2 largest eigen values, somewhat hiding the reality that there are 8 eigen values which are greater than 0.7 in the vector.

Both Kaisers criteria and Jolliffes criteria do not support the answer in Part d, as the first and second eigen values are above 1 and above 0.7, meaning by both Kaisers and Jolliffes criteria, we should expect to see two clusters.
